{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:42:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:42:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"46"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"46","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/46"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.68,0.12,0.15,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"46"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"46","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/46"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"46"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"124"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42954"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a nine-month history of episodic finger pain and colour changes. Her fingers turn white, then blue, and finally red in response to cold exposure. Her thumb is not affected. She has tried avoiding cold exposure but her symptoms have worsened over the past few weeks. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her mother had similar symptoms. She does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. No skin changes, joint swelling, or sclerodactyly are noted. Her erythrocyte sedimentation rate is normal and anti-nuclear antibody test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial pharmacological treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methotrexate","Nifedipine","Prednisolone","Sildenafil","Fluoxetine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of primary Raynaud phenomenon, including triphasic colour changes, sparing of the thumb, family history, and absence of features suggesting secondary causes (such as connective tissue disease). The negative anti-nuclear antibody and normal inflammatory markers support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial pharmacological treatment. Calcium channel blockers are first-line therapy for primary Raynaud phenomenon due to their vasodilatory effects. They are effective in reducing both the frequency and the severity of attacks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESildenafil\u003C/strong\u003E, a phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitor, is considered a second-line treatment for Raynaud phenomenon. While effective, it is reserved for cases that are resistant to calcium channel blockers or when digital ischaemia is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E, a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor, has some evidence for use in Raynaud phenomenon but is considered a second-line option. It is less well-studied than calcium channel blockers for this indication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it is an immunosuppressant used in autoimmune conditions. There is no evidence of underlying connective tissue disease in this case to warrant its use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a corticosteroid that would be indicated if there were features of an underlying inflammatory condition, which are absent here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-pharmacological measures such as keeping warm, avoiding sudden temperature changes, reducing stress, and smoking cessation (if applicable) remain important aspects of management alongside medication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nifedipine, a calcium channel blocker, is first-line pharmacological treatment for primary Raynaud phenomenon.","Primary Raynaud phenomenon is suggested by family history, absence of systemic symptoms, and normal inflammatory markers in a patient experiencing triphasic colour changes of the hands.","Non-pharmacological management including cold avoidance and stress reduction are important initial interventions in patients with primary Raynaud phenomenon."],"references":["Wigley FM, Flavahan NA. Raynaud\u0027s Phenomenon. N Engl J Med 2016; 375:556-65. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27509103/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"46"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T08:37:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T08:37:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"46"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110543"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self